abstract: A whistle-blower’s complaint accused President Trump of using his office to try to get Ukraine to help him in 2020. The acting intelligence chief told Congress that the controversy is “unprecedented.”
snippet: A whistle-blower’s complaint accused President Trump of using his office to try to get Ukraine to help him in 2020. The acting intelligence chief told Congress that the controversy is “unprecedented.”
lead_paragraph: “In the course of my duties, I have received information from multiple U.S. government officials that the President of the United States is using the power of his office to solicit interference from a foreign country in the 2020 U.S. election.” Thus began an explosive criminal complaint drafted by an American intelligence officer and released by the House Intelligence Committee on Thursday.

headline_main: Trump Impeachment Inquiry Updates: The Complaint, the Testimony, the Reaction

abstract: Across the Democratic field, candidates are approaching the impeachment battle as a necessary process, but perhaps not one that ought to redefine their own campaigns.
snippet: Across the Democratic field, candidates are approaching the impeachment battle as a necessary process, but perhaps not one that ought to redefine their own campaigns.
lead_paragraph: KEENE, N.H. — Senator Elizabeth Warren’s message on impeachment was blunt and brief. On a college campus here, Ms. Warren reminded a crowd of hundreds that she had called for President Trump’s impeachment last spring, after the release of Robert S. Mueller III’s report on Russian interference in the 2016 election. Taking action against Mr. Trump, she said then, was “a matter of constitutional responsibility.”

abstract: Ms. Gabbard earned 2 percent support in a new poll in New Hampshire, enough to secure a spot on the stage in Ohio next month.
snippet: Ms. Gabbard earned 2 percent support in a new poll in New Hampshire, enough to secure a spot on the stage in Ohio next month.
lead_paragraph: Representative Tulsi Gabbard of Hawaii became the 12th Democratic presidential candidate to qualify for the October debate after a poll released on Tuesday showed her with 2 percent support in New Hampshire.

abstract: The Democratic National Committee said it would impose slightly higher thresholds to qualify for the November debate.
snippet: The Democratic National Committee said it would impose slightly higher thresholds to qualify for the November debate.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Democratic National Committee said on Monday that it would demand a slight increase in the polling and fund-raising thresholds that presidential candidates must meet in order to qualify for the party’s November primary debate, a move that may once again shrink the field of participating candidates.

headline_main: Democratic Debate Rules Will Make It Harder to Get Onstage
headline_print_headline: New Rules for Democratic Debate Will Make It Harder to Get Onstage
byline_original: By Reid J. Epstein and Matt Stevens

abstract: The presidential candidates have embarked on a four-month sprint to a night of caucuses that remains the single biggest prize in American politics.
snippet: The presidential candidates have embarked on a four-month sprint to a night of caucuses that remains the single biggest prize in American politics.
lead_paragraph: WEBSTER CITY, Iowa — Iowa’s presidential caucuses disenfranchise huge blocs of voters. The state is 91 percent white. It is not easy to get to, or get around in. But to a greater degree than in recent campaigns, this unrepresentative and idiosyncratic state is proving that it is the only electoral battleground that matters for Democrats from now until caucus night on Feb. 3.

headline_main: 2020 Democrats Go All In on Iowa
headline_print_headline: Democratic Candidates Plunge Into Battle to Seize Iowa’s Good Opinion

abstract: Democratic candidates are publicly aligning themselves with union members in hopes of holding onto their support — and winning over those who flipped for President Trump in 2016.
snippet: Democratic candidates are publicly aligning themselves with union members in hopes of holding onto their support — and winning over those who flipped for President Trump in 2016.
lead_paragraph: DETROIT — The Democratic presidential candidates have been chasing labor support all summer, appearing at small union halls and large conferences, and tweeting support for workers at companies like Amazon and Walmart. But now, as the United Automobile Workers, one of the nation’s largest unions, stages a strike that has even drawn words of support from President Trump, Democrats are seizing the moment to align themselves with workers in public and dramatic ways.

headline_main: Warren and Biden Join U.A.W. Picket Lines as Democrats Use Strike to Court Labor
headline_print_headline: Democrats Join U.A.W. Picketers in Show of Solidarity With Labor

abstract: The latest poll numbers from The Des Moines Register and CNN were very good for Elizabeth Warren as she and Joseph R. Biden Jr. broke away from the rest of the Democratic pack.
snippet: The latest poll numbers from The Des Moines Register and CNN were very good for Elizabeth Warren as she and Joseph R. Biden Jr. broke away from the rest of the Democratic pack.
lead_paragraph: DES MOINES — Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts is the new Iowa polling leader, narrowly in first place ahead of former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr., according to a new poll of the state from The Des Moines Register and CNN.

abstract: Senators Warren and Booker shone in a forum focused on the lives of L.G.B.T.Q. Americans.
snippet: Senators Warren and Booker shone in a forum focused on the lives of L.G.B.T.Q. Americans.
lead_paragraph: There was a lot of drama. Senator Cory Booker, by way of greeting, lifted one of the moderators of Friday night’s L.G.B.T.Q. Presidential Forum right off the floor in a great bear hug. Later, an audience member interrupted Senator Amy Klobuchar with what sounded like an appeal to “protect sex workers.”

abstract: A look back at American politics from the year 2050.
snippet: A look back at American politics from the year 2050.
lead_paragraph: A crisis of legitimacy swept across American politics in the second decade of the 21st century. Many people had the general conviction that the old order was corrupt and incompetent. There was an inchoate desire for some radical transformation. This mood swept the Republican Party in 2016 as Donald Trump eviscerated the G.O.P. establishment and it swept through the Democratic Party in 2020.
